<i>Paris's oldest sign
hangs over a twist club.</i>

186
00:13:31,544 --> 00:13:36,118
<i>Rue Mouffetard, a working-class
neighborhood since the 17th century,</i>

187
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:39,058
<i>has recovered its patrician vocation.</i>

188
00:13:39,218 --> 00:13:42,290
<i>Beetroot is cheaper
that on the Right Bank.</i>

189
00:13:42,455 --> 00:13:43,900
<i>But not paintings.</i>

190
00:13:44,057 --> 00:13:48,233
<i>This ancient Roman way
that trembled under a Praetorian march,</i>

191
00:13:48,394 --> 00:13:51,568
<i>now leads to an unfathomable future.</i>

192
00:13:51,931 --> 00:13:53,968
<i>There are cabarets, galleries,</i>

193
00:13:54,133 --> 00:13:56,113
a theatre.

194
00:13:56,269 --> 00:13:59,341
<i>10 years on, these images
will be more disorientating</i>

195
00:13:59,505 --> 00:14:01,576
<i>than those of Paris 1900.</i>

196
00:14:19,525 --> 00:14:21,596
<i>But Rue Mouffetard's metamorphosis</i>

197
00:14:21,961 --> 00:14:25,841
<i>applies to half of Paris,
the most picturesque half.</i>

198
00:14:26,332 --> 00:14:29,040
<i>Ifs easy to praise
urban transformation</i>

199
00:14:29,202 --> 00:14:32,149
<i>when 1 in 20 homes
has no electricity,</i>

200
00:14:32,305 --> 00:14:34,251
<i>1 in 12 no water.</i>

201
00:14:35,141 --> 00:14:38,554
<i>Yet carriages often lose
the charm of pumpkins,</i>

202
00:14:38,911 --> 00:14:42,256
<i>Europe's future capital
should include in its plan</i>

203
00:14:42,415 --> 00:14:46,056
<i>that modest treasure
defined in one word:</i>

204
00:14:46,219 --> 00:14:47,357
<i>"friendliness."</i>

205
00:14:47,620 --> 00:14:49,190
Why do you like this area?

206
00:14:49,355 --> 00:14:53,360
I love it here.
The friendliness...

207
00:14:54,494 --> 00:14:58,032
It's "La Mouffe."
It's genuine.

208
00:14:58,197 --> 00:15:00,973
It's "La Mouffe."
You can't leave.

209
00:15:01,134 --> 00:15:03,205
I wouldn't move for anything.

210
00:15:03,369 --> 00:15:05,178
Bury me in this street.

211
00:15:06,906 --> 00:15:11,582
Is there a question
of you being rehoused afterwards?

212
00:15:11,944 --> 00:15:13,480
- Sure.
- Where will you go?

213
00:15:14,981 --> 00:15:16,983
Like everyone.
We'll look for a place.

214
00:15:17,150 --> 00:15:20,063
Somewhere nice and calm.
And friendly.

215
00:15:20,253 --> 00:15:22,995
<i>Oh, if you knew Maubeuge</i>

216
00:15:23,589 --> 00:15:25,535
<i>I knew great love</i>

217
00:15:25,691 --> 00:15:28,137
<i>In distant lands</i>

218
00:15:41,941 --> 00:15:43,648
<i>POETRY 2000</i>

219
00:15:44,043 --> 00:15:45,579
<i>NIGHT BELL FOR THE SACRAMENTS</i>

220
00:15:54,320 --> 00:15:55,162
<i>DANGEROUS DOG</i>

221
00:15:55,321 --> 00:15:56,959
What will you miss most?

222
00:15:57,190 --> 00:15:59,636
The alley.

223
00:15:59,992 --> 00:16:03,201
- This place?
- The back room. And here.

224
00:16:04,664 --> 00:16:07,338
Anything, everything.

225
00:16:08,301 --> 00:16:09,712
You have to admit it.

226
00:16:10,069 --> 00:16:11,309
This is our home.

227
00:16:11,471 --> 00:16:13,246
Anywhere else we'd feel deported.

228
00:17:49,101 --> 00:17:49,806
The present solutions,

229
00:17:50,202 --> 00:17:54,082
which are fastidious,
monotonous, inhuman,

230
00:17:54,206 --> 00:17:56,186
dreary, ugly and all that...

231
00:17:56,342 --> 00:18:00,154
arise because no one conceives it
any other way.

232
00:18:00,313 --> 00:18:02,759
The basic aim is not that at all.

233
00:18:03,115 --> 00:18:04,389
The aim is money.

234
00:18:04,550 --> 00:18:05,392
It's money.

235
00:18:05,551 --> 00:18:09,522
That's why another technique
is possible.

236
00:18:09,689 --> 00:18:11,691
We must explore techniques.

237
00:18:11,857 --> 00:18:16,602
But first we determine the context.

238
00:18:16,762 --> 00:18:20,232
Not a context where land
costs 150 000 francs the square meter.

239
00:18:20,399 --> 00:18:21,639
It's impossible.

240
00:18:21,801 --> 00:18:24,407
That context calls for skyscrapers.

241
00:18:24,570 --> 00:18:27,813
Skyscrapers can be beautiful,
but in Paris...

242
00:18:28,174 --> 00:18:29,152
It could work...

243
00:18:29,308 --> 00:18:33,620
but multiplying them
like in the 15th district is ridiculous.

244
00:18:39,185 --> 00:18:41,461
What would you do on this site?

245
00:18:41,621 --> 00:18:43,157
Well, ideally...

246
00:18:44,190 --> 00:18:46,295
I'd start by planting trees.

247
00:18:46,459 --> 00:18:47,665
Trees and greenery.

248
00:18:47,827 --> 00:18:50,103
We're asking you to house people.

249
00:18:50,262 --> 00:18:53,471
And then...
We can't narrow it down to sites.

250
00:18:53,633 --> 00:18:55,271
It's a global approach.

251
00:18:55,434 --> 00:18:58,313
We can start imagining from there.

252
00:18:59,605 --> 00:19:03,382
Tiny little things hidden in the trees,

253
00:19:03,542 --> 00:19:05,351
like birds,
and near them,

254
00:19:05,511 --> 00:19:07,513
in the trees and greenery...

255
00:19:07,680 --> 00:19:09,125
A ground floor'?

256
00:19:09,682 --> 00:19:11,753
A ground floor and upper floors,

257
00:19:11,917 --> 00:19:13,294
as high as the trees.

258
00:19:13,452 --> 00:19:16,729
A bit higher, but not much.

259
00:19:16,889 --> 00:19:18,800
Always in contact with nature.

260
00:19:19,158 --> 00:19:21,729
On every level,

261
00:19:21,894 --> 00:19:25,535
everyone will have
their own little garden.

262
00:19:25,698 --> 00:19:26,802
Little ponds.

263
00:19:27,166 --> 00:19:30,670
Kids playing there like monkeys
or squirrels,

264
00:19:30,836 --> 00:19:33,612
flying from tree to tree,
to each house.

265
00:19:33,773 --> 00:19:35,480
We could create wonders,

266
00:19:35,641 --> 00:19:39,248
joyful, connected to nature.
You see?

267
00:19:39,412 --> 00:19:42,222
- You know Babar?
- That's it. Right.

268
00:19:42,515 --> 00:19:46,327
Célesteville.
I totally agree with Célesteville.

269
00:19:46,485 --> 00:19:49,159
No point being rigid and cold.

270
00:19:49,321 --> 00:19:51,528
Not a suburban Célesteville,

271
00:19:51,691 --> 00:19:53,762
each house saying:
"I'm the best."

272
00:19:53,926 --> 00:19:56,907
No. People happy to live together.

273
00:19:57,263 --> 00:19:58,674
Exactly. I agree.

274
00:19:58,831 --> 00:20:02,335
It reflects how we dislike
living together.

275
00:20:02,501 --> 00:20:04,708
- It pisses us off.
- Right.

276
00:20:04,870 --> 00:20:06,508
We hear the neighbors.

277
00:20:06,672 --> 00:20:11,553
But what you're saying means
other changes besides architecture.

278
00:20:11,711 --> 00:20:14,453
At one point architects must say:

279
00:20:14,613 --> 00:20:18,652
"it's great to be together.
Not boring or ponderous."

280
00:20:18,818 --> 00:20:20,593
Are the people happy

281
00:20:20,786 --> 00:20:22,424
in this neighborhood?

282
00:20:22,588 --> 00:20:25,592
Some are very happy, but others...

283
00:20:25,758 --> 00:20:28,534
They say this neighborhood is a bit...

284
00:20:28,694 --> 00:20:31,436
A lot of gossip goes on here.

285
00:20:31,597 --> 00:20:35,443
Especially here, in these projects.
They're very big.

286
00:20:35,601 --> 00:20:40,209
A lot of people. All nosing
into everyone else's business.

287
00:20:40,372 --> 00:20:44,878
Do you think the people here
would move out if they could?

288
00:20:45,244 --> 00:20:46,416
A lot would.

289
00:20:46,579 --> 00:20:47,717
Yes, a lot.

290
00:20:47,880 --> 00:20:50,554
- Would you?
- Right away.

291
00:20:50,716 --> 00:20:53,788
If I had a chance,
I'd leave immediately.

292
00:20:53,953 --> 00:20:56,763
- What stops you...
- The rehousing issue.

293
00:20:58,290 --> 00:20:59,633
- What did you say?
- Me?

294
00:20:59,792 --> 00:21:02,329
- Yes, what?
- That it's prehistoric.

295
00:21:02,495 --> 00:21:03,565
What's prehistoric?

296
00:21:03,729 --> 00:21:05,003
- The walls.
- The walls?

297
00:21:08,701 --> 00:21:10,806
