"Christians and the thirst for justice "</i>

335
00:23:24,703 --> 00:23:27,479
<i>Reading classes for North Africans</i>

336
00:24:12,217 --> 00:24:14,197
- Good news.
- You're rehoused?

337
00:24:14,553 --> 00:24:16,794
Yes, I'm rehoused.

338
00:24:16,956 --> 00:24:19,698
How did you feel hearing that?

339
00:24:19,858 --> 00:24:22,930
- I felt like crying.
- You cried?

340
00:24:23,095 --> 00:24:28,545
Yes. I think it was
the happiest day of my life.

341
00:24:28,701 --> 00:24:31,614
- How long had you waited?
- Seven years.

342
00:24:31,770 --> 00:24:34,614
Did you apply to the local council?

343
00:24:34,773 --> 00:24:36,480
Yes. And we waited.

344
00:24:36,642 --> 00:24:40,681
Then one day,
a nice gentleman looked into my case.

345
00:24:40,846 --> 00:24:44,953
Then on Wednesday, I got a letter
saying I'd been rehoused.

346
00:24:45,117 --> 00:24:47,529
I felt so happy I could cry.

347
00:24:47,686 --> 00:24:48,756
The postman brought it'?

348
00:24:48,921 --> 00:24:51,959
Yes. He even waited to hear the news!

349
00:24:52,124 --> 00:24:54,764
- He waited?
- For me to read it.

350
00:24:54,927 --> 00:24:58,898
To know if we were rehoused
or we had to wait.

351
00:24:59,064 --> 00:25:02,511
When he heard the news,
he was as happy as me.

352
00:25:02,668 --> 00:25:04,705
It was the morning mail?

353
00:25:04,870 --> 00:25:06,941
You waited all day for your husband?

354
00:25:07,106 --> 00:25:08,847
No, he comes home for lunch.

355
00:25:09,008 --> 00:25:11,648
When he heard,
he was as happy as me.

356
00:25:11,810 --> 00:25:13,721
How did you tell him?

357
00:25:13,879 --> 00:25:14,983
I didn't say anything.

358
00:25:15,147 --> 00:25:19,186
The table was set,
I'd put the envelope on his plate.

359
00:25:19,551 --> 00:25:22,760
When he came in
he saw it on his plate.

360
00:25:22,921 --> 00:25:26,198
He sort of guessed.
But he wasn't sure.

361
00:25:26,558 --> 00:25:28,799
When he read it
he was so happy.

362
00:25:28,961 --> 00:25:30,497
Was he in a good mood before?

363
00:25:30,662 --> 00:25:32,642
He's always in a good mood.

364
00:25:32,798 --> 00:25:35,677
But he could hardly eat.

365
00:25:35,834 --> 00:25:37,814
Had you seen the new place?

366
00:25:38,303 --> 00:25:40,214
You just knew you had one.

367
00:25:40,572 --> 00:25:41,744
We knew. Yes.

368
00:25:41,907 --> 00:25:46,014
- You've visited it?
- Yes. Yesterday.

369
00:25:46,178 --> 00:25:48,784
- Your impressions?
- I don't know.

370
00:25:48,947 --> 00:25:52,588
When I saw those big rooms
I felt lost.

371
00:25:52,751 --> 00:25:57,166
I felt... I don't know.
I had no idea it was like that.

372
00:25:57,322 --> 00:25:58,164
How many rooms?

373
00:25:58,323 --> 00:26:01,236
3 bedrooms, a living room,

374
00:26:01,593 --> 00:26:05,541
kitchen, water closet, toilet,
and a hallway.

375
00:26:05,697 --> 00:26:09,042
Big closets.
I don't know where I'll put things

376
00:26:09,201 --> 00:26:11,579
as we'll have so much space.

377
00:26:11,737 --> 00:26:14,741
- You'll arrange it.
- I'll find a way.

378
00:26:14,907 --> 00:26:17,319
Have you thought about the move'?

379
00:26:17,676 --> 00:26:20,850
Oh, yes!
My husband and I are planning it.

380
00:26:21,013 --> 00:26:23,186
We haven't stopped.

381
00:26:23,348 --> 00:26:26,625
It's all we talk about,
our new home.

382
00:26:27,920 --> 00:26:32,733
Do you think it will improve
your private life'?

383
00:26:32,925 --> 00:26:36,600
- That's for sure.
- A change in your life style?

384
00:26:36,762 --> 00:26:39,265
We're not free with the kids around.

385
00:26:39,631 --> 00:26:42,805
They'll have their room
and we'll have ours.

386
00:26:42,968 --> 00:26:45,949
We'll feel like young newlyweds again!

387
00:26:48,273 --> 00:26:50,810
- How many children do you have?
- Eight.

388
00:26:51,009 --> 00:26:52,989
And a little niece we adopted.

389
00:26:53,145 --> 00:26:54,123
An adopted niece?

390
00:26:54,279 --> 00:26:56,725
We lost a sister-in-law recently.

391
00:26:56,882 --> 00:26:59,886
We placed her 6 children in the family.

392
00:27:00,052 --> 00:27:03,795
- You took a child?
- Yes, a little girl aged 9.

393
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:06,095
- So you have 9 children?
- Nine.

394
00:27:06,258 --> 00:27:07,931
Plus you and your husband?

395
00:27:08,093 --> 00:27:11,870
How do you manage
to live in this room?

396
00:27:12,030 --> 00:27:14,101
I have a large bed

397
00:27:14,299 --> 00:27:18,111
in the bedroom,
a big bed where I put 4 children.

398
00:27:18,270 --> 00:27:21,376
I have a folding bedstead where 2 sleep.

399
00:27:21,740 --> 00:27:23,845
And a cot for my youngest.

400
00:27:24,009 --> 00:27:26,785
This child sleeps in the dining room,

401
00:27:26,945 --> 00:27:28,947
between me and my husband.

402
00:27:29,148 --> 00:27:32,129
Dining room...
the room we use as a kitchen.

403
00:27:32,284 --> 00:27:35,026
We separate it
so the kids aren't with us.

404
00:27:35,187 --> 00:27:37,098
And when a child falls ill?

405
00:27:37,256 --> 00:27:40,203
He stays in bed but he can't rest.

406
00:27:42,694 --> 00:27:46,403
What do you think of your bedroom'?
Tell me.

407
00:27:46,765 --> 00:27:49,837
- It's beautiful.
- How will you feel?

408
00:27:50,002 --> 00:27:53,108
Better, as we'll be warmer.

409
00:27:53,272 --> 00:27:56,116
Warmer?
But there were four of you.

410
00:27:57,009 --> 00:27:59,387
- You'll sleep better?
- Yes.

411
00:27:59,745 --> 00:28:02,817
- This room is for you three?
- The three boys.

412
00:28:02,981 --> 00:28:04,688
The three boys' bedroom.

413
00:28:04,850 --> 00:28:07,194
Now we'll look at the girls' room.

414
00:28:08,453 --> 00:28:13,095
Come on, girls. This is your room.
What do you think?

415
00:28:13,792 --> 00:28:14,770
It's fine.

416
00:28:14,927 --> 00:28:17,032
Happy to have your own room?

417
00:28:18,797 --> 00:28:22,006
You won't have to sleep
at grandma's now.

418
00:28:22,167 --> 00:28:25,444
You won't have to go out at night.

419
00:28:25,804 --> 00:28:27,875
Was it hard sleeping there?

420
00:28:28,040 --> 00:28:30,748
Especially with the "Harkis" close by.

421
00:28:30,909 --> 00:28:33,389
She was scared of going past them.

422
00:28:33,779 --> 00:28:36,191
We had to take her every night.

423
00:28:36,381 --> 00:28:38,827
She was so scared.

424
00:28:38,984 --> 00:28:41,863
Hey, your chewing gum!

425
00:28:42,020 --> 00:28:44,000
Is it still the same school?

426
00:28:44,156 --> 00:28:46,397
Until the end of the year.

427
00:28:46,758 --> 00:28:50,865
- Then somewhere closer'?
- They'll go to the local school.

428
00:28:51,029 --> 00:28:53,873
Do you mind changing schools?

429
00:28:56,068 --> 00:28:59,777
You have a schoolmaster?

430
00:28:59,938 --> 00:29:02,111
No, a schoolmistress.

431
00:29:02,274 --> 00:29:05,278
Do you mind leaving her
or don't you care?

432
00:29:06,178 --> 00:29:07,156
Not bothered?

433
00:29:07,312 --> 00:29:10,987
No, a schoolmistress
ls a schoolmistress.

434
00:29:11,183 --> 00:29:12,753
Don't climb, you'll fall.

435
00:29:12,918 --> 00:29:15,159
The boys are all watching us.

436
00:29:15,320 --> 00:29:18,858
Sure they are.
Nobody knows you.

437
00:29:19,024 --> 00:29:21,129
Look. Everyone's watching you.

438
00:29:21,293 --> 00:29:22,499
He's on the grass.

439
00:29:22,861 --> 00:29:26,035
We didn't have windows
to look out of before.

440
00:29:29,768 --> 00:29:31,406
Are you happy?

441
00:29:36,441 --> 00:29:40,856
She said: "First I opened the door,
I found myself in the kitchen."

442
00:29:41,780 --> 00:29:43,384
Can you see the school?

443
00:29:43,548 --> 00:29:45,892
No. It's on the other side.

444
00:29:46,051 --> 00:29:48,031
- Who is'?
- The school.

445
00:29:48,186 --> 00:29:49,927
Oh, the school!

446
00:29:53,191 --> 00:29:55,899
Behave yourselves.
And don't fall off.

447
00:29:56,061 --> 00:29:59,975
Want to? Want to?

448
00:30:02,034 --> 00:30:03,308
What did you say?

449
00:30:03,468 --> 00:30:06,813
- Look at the statue.
- You see, there's a statue.

450
00:30:06,972 --> 00:30:08,110
With a star.

451
00:30:08,307 --> 00:30:09,445
And a star.

452
00:30:13,979 --> 00:30:16,050
And bikes hanging!

453
00:30:25,891 --> 00:30:26,324
What do you expect from life'?
Want to continue?

454
00:30:26,325 --> 00:30:29,204
What do you expect from life'?
Want to continue?

455
00:30:29,361 --> 00:30:32,137
Sure. I still like it.

456
00:30:32,297 --> 00:30:34,208
I don't plan to give up.

457
00:30:34,366 --> 00:30:38,007
You see yourselves
as stockbrokers?

458
00:30:38,170 --> 00:30:39,877
- Hardly.
- Not that far.

459
00:30:40,038 --> 00:30:41,540
Then <i>as</i> what?

460
00:30:42,607 --> 00:30:44,587
- Head clerk.
- Service head.

461
00:30:44,943 --> 00:30:47,253
Service head after, if possible.

462
00:30:47,412 --> 00:30:49,221
And then? No higher'?

463
00:30:49,381 --> 00:30:51,918
Managing director.
Then boss.

464
00:30:52,084 --> 00:30:55,554
- Nothing more ambitious?
- That's it. Sorry.

465
00:30:55,921 --> 00:30:57,366
Why?

466
00:30:59,958 --> 00:31:01,562
You can't be a gopher forever.

467
00:31:01,927 --> 00:31:04,908
Sure. What's good
about being the boss?

468
00:31:05,063 --> 00:31:08,840
Earning more'?
Having more power?

469
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:11,412
- Sure, I'd like that.
- Power.

470
00:31:11,570 --> 00:31:13,345
You'd like power?

471
00:31:14,339 --> 00:31:16,376
What is money, in your view?

472
00:31:16,541 --> 00:31:18,418
- Lots of things.
- For instance?

473
00:31:19,244 --> 00:31:23,124
With money, you can eat.
That's the first thing.

474
00:31:23,281 --> 00:31:25,056
And then what?

475
00:31:26,551 --> 00:31:28,531
You can have a lot of fun.

476
00:31:29,888 --> 00:31:31,492
What kind of fun?

477
00:31:34,159 --> 00:31:35,604
Entertainments...

478
00:31:36,328 --> 00:31:37,602
The theatre.

479
00:31:37,963 --> 00:31:40,273
That's entertainment. Movies...

480
00:31:41,433 --> 00:31:43,037
What else?

481
00:31:44,970 --> 00:31:48,008
- It's a bit limited.
- I don't know.

482
00:31:51,343 --> 00:31:56,088
Do you have interests outside
your work and entertainment?

483
00:31:56,248 --> 00:31:59,559
Other things you care about?
Like current events?

484
00:31:59,918 --> 00:32:01,192
Yes, of course.

485
00:32:01,353 --> 00:32:03,264
Because they influence the Stock Market?

486
00:32:03,422 --> 00:32:04,423
It depends.

487
00:32:04,589 --> 00:32:09,299
What sort of things?
Like "major events"?

488
00:32:09,461 --> 00:32:11,338
Yes, for the Stock Market.

489
00:32:11,530 --> 00:32:13,407
What recent major events?

490
00:32:13,565 --> 00:32:16,341
The Algiers putsch.

491
00:32:16,501 --> 00:32:20,005
- I'll inform the Association.
- Go ahead.

492
00:32:20,172 --> 00:32:23,619
What gives you the right
to make kids work?

493
00:32:23,975 --> 00:32:25,511
We're not asking them secrets.

494
00:32:25,677 --> 00:32:29,124
There are no secrets.
You're interviewing minors.

495
00:32:29,281 --> 00:32:31,693
Want to ask my toddler his views?

496
00:32:32,050 --> 00:32:34,291
Good idea. Bring him in.

497
00:32:34,453 --> 00:32:38,060
I feel like answering, that's all.

498
00:32:38,223 --> 00:32:40,533
What's it to him'?

499
00:32:42,327 --> 00:32:43,465
We're filming.

500
00:32:43,628 --> 00:32:46,370
You're not obliged to answer.

501
00:32:46,531 --> 00:32:50,411
May I ask how long
you've been coming here?

502
00:32:50,569 --> 00:32:52,048
Over 25 years.

503
00:32:52,204 --> 00:32:55,276
Over 25 years.
And you like it here?

504
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:56,544
It's my profession.

505
00:32:56,708 --> 00:32:58,654
- You enjoy it?
- Very much.

506
00:32:59,010 --> 00:33:01,115
Was it by choice?

507
00:33:02,481 --> 00:33:06,657
When I finished my studies,
I didn't plan on the Stock Market.

508
00:33:07,018 --> 00:33:08,998
But I had acquaintances.

509
00:33:09,154 --> 00:33:12,397
I got in through them
and I never left.

510
00:33:12,557 --> 00:33:13,729
What do you do?

511
00:33:14,125 --> 00:33:16,002
I'm a stockbroker.

512
00:33:16,161 --> 00:33:18,004
Can I ask a general question

513
00:33:18,163 --> 00:33:20,439
to do with your work
and other issues?

514
00:33:20,599 --> 00:33:22,510
What does money mean to you?

515
00:33:23,602 --> 00:33:26,378
It's a means of existence.

516
00:33:26,571 --> 00:33:29,575
Which stocks have risen most today?

517
00:33:29,741 --> 00:33:31,345
- Cofirep.
- What's that?

518
00:33:31,510 --> 00:33:33,319
An oil research company.

519
00:33:33,478 --> 00:33:37,290
The day Algeria was in the worst state
since '58.

520
00:33:37,449 --> 00:33:40,430
Yes. The market is dependent,
as I said.

521
00:33:40,585 --> 00:33:43,065
Is it a coincidence?

522
00:33:43,221 --> 00:33:45,360
It's not a coincidence.

523
00:33:45,524 --> 00:33:47,595
Not a coincidence.

524
00:33:47,759 --> 00:33:50,706
It's the big investors who said...

525
00:33:51,062 --> 00:33:54,566
It's empirical.
There's no explanation.

526
00:33:54,733 --> 00:33:57,043
It's a state of mind.
A psychosis.

527
00:33:57,202 --> 00:34:00,115
Before, it would have dropped 10%.
It's up 7%.

528
00:34:00,272 --> 00:34:03,276
It's serious if laws don't apply now.

529
00:34:03,441 --> 00:34:05,182
It's not about laws.

530
00:34:05,343 --> 00:34:08,790
No. The gentleman means
"natural laws."

531
00:34:09,147 --> 00:34:11,024
Not legislative laws.

532
00:34:11,182 --> 00:34:14,561
They have no bearing here anymore.

533
00:34:14,719 --> 00:34:17,598
You said:
"Woe to the man with judgment."

534
00:34:17,756 --> 00:34:22,296
Yes, if he uses his judgment here,
he's ruined.

535
00:34:22,460 --> 00:34:25,066
Really? Do explain.

536
00:34:25,230 --> 00:34:29,736
He mentioned Cofirep.
I didn't follow the trading today.

537
00:34:30,101 --> 00:34:34,140
He said events in Algeria
should have made stocks fall 10%.

538
00:34:34,306 --> 00:34:35,307
They rose.

539
00:34:35,473 --> 00:34:37,146
The only ones that did.

540
00:34:37,309 --> 00:34:40,518
Yesterday he'd have said:
"Algeria looks bad.

541
00:34:40,679 --> 00:34:43,626
- "Something will happen."
- I'll sell!

542
00:34:43,782 --> 00:34:46,422
"I had news from the Algiers police.

543
00:34:46,585 --> 00:34:49,566
"Something awful will happen tonight."

544
00:34:49,721 --> 00:34:53,498
He would have sold yesterday.
Today he's right.

545
00:34:53,658 --> 00:34:58,198
Right about the facts.
But not about the effects.

546
00:34:58,363 --> 00:35:00,070
A personal question?

547
00:35:00,231 --> 00:35:02,142
When you hear bad news,

548
00:35:02,300 --> 00:35:06,749
is your first reaction how
it will affect the Stock Market or...

549
00:35:07,105 --> 00:35:10,416
No, our first reaction is patriotic.

550
00:35:10,575 --> 00:35:11,849
True for everyone?

551
00:35:12,210 --> 00:35:15,384
- I speak for my generation.
- I'd say the opposite.

552
00:35:15,547 --> 00:35:17,390
Him and me, I'm sure.

553
00:35:17,549 --> 00:35:22,430
I'd have said the opposite.
Here's a striking example.

554
00:35:22,587 --> 00:35:25,193
February 6th, everyone came out.

555
00:35:25,357 --> 00:35:29,305
We sang <i>The</i> Marseillaise
as Daladier had resigned.

556
00:35:29,461 --> 00:35:31,737
Everyone began buying shares.

557
00:35:31,896 --> 00:35:36,743
3 months later, the radicals in power
rejected the government.

558
00:35:36,901 --> 00:35:41,145
Everyone who'd bought shares
took the rap.

559
00:35:41,306 --> 00:35:46,517
Until Flandin, a moderate radical,
returned to power.

560
00:35:46,678 --> 00:35:50,785
In conclusion, I say:
So much for your national ideals.

561
00:35:51,149 --> 00:35:52,856
"Wipe your feet on them."

562
00:35:53,218 --> 00:35:57,667
The same facts,
the same political situation,

563
00:35:57,822 --> 00:36:00,735
the same political
and economic situation

564
00:36:00,892 --> 00:36:06,308
can have the opposite effect

565
00:36:06,464 --> 00:36:10,571
at a different moment in time.

566
00:36:10,735 --> 00:36:14,512
The same situation

567
00:36:14,673 --> 00:36:16,710
can go one way today,

568
00:36:16,875 --> 00:36:19,719
three years from now,
it can go another way.

569
00:36:19,878 --> 00:36:23,223
A striking example in current events.

570
00:36:23,381 --> 00:36:26,692
- You see it everywhere.
- A striking example.

571
00:36:26,851 --> 00:36:30,355
You have stock in Northern Rail.

572
00:36:30,522 --> 00:36:31,728
It's worth 42 francs.

573
00:36:31,890 --> 00:36:36,566
Everyone says it's worth
70 to 80 francs, in portfolios.

574
00:36:36,728 --> 00:36:40,801
It never goes up.
Pompidou gets in, it's worth 53.

575
00:36:40,965 --> 00:36:42,342
That's the Rothschilds.

576
00:36:42,500 --> 00:36:45,811
Nothing had changed about the affair.

577
00:36:45,970 --> 00:36:47,449
People said: "Really? Good."

578
00:36:47,605 --> 00:36:51,815
The Rothschilds bought it
to back their candidate.

579
00:36:53,211 --> 00:36:56,192
They said: "Hello, investment company?
Onwards!"

580
00:36:56,347 --> 00:36:58,327
And everyone went for it.

581
00:37:57,709 --> 00:38:00,246
The peso won't be devalued.

582
00:38:00,411 --> 00:38:04,587
Peronism nowadays is nothing like

583
00:38:04,749 --> 00:38:07,730
the Peronist era ten years ago.

584
00:38:07,886 --> 00:38:09,024
Nothing like it.

585
00:38:09,387 --> 00:38:12,425
The Peronists will help.

586
00:39:00,505 --> 00:39:02,678
"Some play the Market
Other pick pockets

587
00:39:02,841 --> 00:39:04,718
POET'S FAIR

588
00:39:04,843 --> 00:39:06,618
"But I don't give a damn

589
00:39:06,778 --> 00:39:09,088
"I'm a very happy man

590
00:39:09,447 --> 00:39:10,619
"Yes, yes, yes...

591
00:39:10,815 --> 00:39:15,025
"Some can't stand it
Without cash, life's a gambit

592
00:39:15,386 --> 00:39:19,334
"But let me tell you

593
00:39:19,490 --> 00:39:21,060
"I don't know any song

594
00:39:21,426 --> 00:39:23,531
"I can't even sing along

595
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:26,699
"But when broke, I feel wings grow

596
00:39:26,865 --> 00:39:29,778
"When broke, I'm graceful as a doe

597
00:39:29,934 --> 00:39:33,006
"I'm like a fish in his sea

598
00:39:33,371 --> 00:39:35,749
"I'm happy as any king can be."

599
00:39:40,879 --> 00:39:43,917
Tell me when to speak.

600
00:39:47,685 --> 00:39:51,098
Monsieur Sulta,
Prince Murat's envoy,

601
00:39:53,391 --> 00:39:54,927
will present the doves

602
00:39:55,793 --> 00:39:59,366
to the Poets' Muse of 1962.

603
00:40:00,131 --> 00:40:02,702
"Within sight of my yearning eyes,

604
00:40:02,867 --> 00:40:06,110
"Soar aloft, bearer of messages,

605
00:40:06,471 --> 00:40:11,614
"Return to me,
Show me white hands."

606
00:40:11,776 --> 00:40:12,686
Bravo.

607
00:40:12,844 --> 00:40:14,084
Lovely.

608
00:40:17,548 --> 00:40:19,858
They didn't go very far.

609
00:40:20,018 --> 00:40:25,468
Cutie, why won't you fly?
Haven't I been nice to you'?

610
00:40:25,623 --> 00:40:27,762
Silly. You're not beautiful.

611
00:40:27,926 --> 00:40:29,803
<i>The dove is not beautiful.</i>

612
00:40:29,961 --> 00:40:33,067
<i>It's a dirty, cruel creature.</i>

613
00:40:33,698 --> 00:40:38,511
<i>The owl is beautiful, pleasant, deep.</i>

614
00:41:05,830 --> 00:41:08,777
<i>Why search for beauty in a dove</i>

615
00:41:08,933 --> 00:41:10,571
<i>and poetry in poets?</i>

616
00:41:10,735 --> 00:41:13,773
<i>When you have owls,
painters, cosmonauts,</i>

617
00:41:13,938 --> 00:41:15,884
<i>Inventors, lovers...</i>

618
00:41:16,107 --> 00:41:18,018
<i>And Pierrot the cabbie.</i>

619
00:41:18,176 --> 00:41:21,214
P.P., licensed tire repairman

620
00:41:26,684 --> 00:41:28,459
Stay put...

621
00:41:36,928 --> 00:41:38,930
Well, well.

622
00:41:39,097 --> 00:41:41,077
What do you think?

623
00:41:41,232 --> 00:41:44,941
Interesting.
How long have you been doing this?

624
00:41:45,103 --> 00:41:47,140
- About a year.
- A year?

625
00:41:47,505 --> 00:41:51,954
A year. I do it
when I feel like painting.

626
00:41:52,110 --> 00:41:55,091
Sometimes two weeks
or a month go by.

627
00:41:55,246 --> 00:41:56,691
How long did this take?

628
00:41:56,848 --> 00:41:57,952
This one...

629
00:41:58,649 --> 00:42:02,153
I worked on it for about 20 hours.

630
00:42:02,520 --> 00:42:05,126
Getting the colors right is tricky.

631
00:42:05,289 --> 00:42:08,668
I do several sessions.
Not continually

632
00:42:08,826 --> 00:42:12,933
Sometimes I work <i>2</i> hours a day.
Sometimes 3 or 5.

633
00:42:13,097 --> 00:42:16,010
Or not at all.
It just depends.

634
00:42:16,167 --> 00:42:18,909
- Is it relaxing?
- It's a hobby. I enjoy it.

635
00:42:20,171 --> 00:42:21,878
What are you depicting?

636
00:42:22,040 --> 00:42:26,511
- I wanted to depict Christ.
- Right.

637
00:42:26,677 --> 00:42:28,987
With the angels overhead.

638
00:42:29,947 --> 00:42:33,554
And the...
What are they called in Spain?

639
00:42:34,185 --> 00:42:36,597
The priests...

640
00:42:36,754 --> 00:42:39,234
You know, the monks with hats on.

641
00:42:39,590 --> 00:42:43,732
- The processions.
- The monks, angels and nuns.

642
00:42:45,129 --> 00:42:47,905
It's the man who died
at the foot of the cross.

643
00:42:48,066 --> 00:42:51,070
Did certain painters influence you?

644
00:42:51,235 --> 00:42:54,546
No, I want to follow my own vision.

645
00:42:54,705 --> 00:42:55,979
I don't like copying.

646
00:42:56,140 --> 00:42:58,086
Follow your own vision?

647
00:42:58,242 --> 00:43:02,088
Not always do the same painting,
like they do.

648
00:43:02,246 --> 00:43:04,954
You have to find something new.

649
00:43:05,116 --> 00:43:08,757
Not copy people.
Find something new.

650
00:43:08,920 --> 00:43:10,957
That's worthwhile.

651
00:43:12,323 --> 00:43:14,166
Here's a modern art influence.

652
00:43:14,325 --> 00:43:16,669
It's modern art, yes.

653
00:43:17,361 --> 00:43:22,572
I get around a lot
but I haven't seen work like this.

654
00:43:23,835 --> 00:43:26,008
Let's hope it will do well.

655
00:43:26,170 --> 00:43:28,741
I have a dozen finished paintings.

656
00:43:28,906 --> 00:43:31,045
In oils?

657
00:43:31,776 --> 00:43:34,586
- On canvas?
- Oils on canvas.

658
00:43:35,379 --> 00:43:39,327
The hardest thing to get right
is the colors.

659
00:43:39,684 --> 00:43:41,823
You have a system for colors?

660
00:43:41,986 --> 00:43:46,799
I focus, I study...
Then I put the color down.

661
00:43:46,958 --> 00:43:49,962
It's hard with pale colors like that.

662
00:43:50,128 --> 00:43:51,698
Do you draw first?

663
00:43:51,863 --> 00:43:56,073
I draw first,
then I do the colors.

664
00:43:57,368 --> 00:43:59,006
It's very difficult.

665
00:43:59,170 --> 00:44:02,640
Once a color is painted in,
changing it is...

666
00:44:02,807 --> 00:44:05,913
It all has to blend in together.

667
00:44:06,944 --> 00:44:09,857
I think I'll come up with something.

668
00:44:10,014 --> 00:44:12,324
- Will you exhibit?
- Maybe later on.

669
00:44:12,683 --> 00:44:16,756
- Where?
- I don't know. A local gallery.

670
00:44:17,788 --> 00:44:20,359
How do people react generally?

671
00:44:20,758 --> 00:44:24,365
They like them,
the colors, the whole thing.

672
00:44:24,729 --> 00:44:28,040
Do they say why they like them?

673
00:44:28,166 --> 00:44:30,077
Yes, they find them cheerful.

674
00:44:40,711 --> 00:44:43,123
How long is it on'?
A month?

675
00:44:44,448 --> 00:44:45,984
Christ and the angels.

676
00:44:46,184 --> 00:44:47,754
Is this another study?

677
00:44:48,186 --> 00:44:52,362
Yes, a study done on...

678
00:44:53,157 --> 00:44:57,299
How can I explain?
A tire ad.

679
00:44:58,829 --> 00:45:02,777
It was out up and dented.
Look at the back.

680
00:45:04,202 --> 00:45:06,079
Dented with a hammer.

681
00:45:06,237 --> 00:45:11,346
I brought the lines out in paint.
It's Cosmic Man.

682
00:45:11,709 --> 00:45:13,154
Why?

683
00:45:13,311 --> 00:45:16,155
The subject appeared like that.

684
00:45:16,314 --> 00:45:19,124
I wanted to accentuate the colors

685
00:45:19,283 --> 00:45:22,127
to describe the character of the cosmos,

686
00:45:22,286 --> 00:45:24,357
based on the dents on the back.

687
00:45:24,722 --> 00:45:27,134
What is the character of the cosmos?

688
00:45:27,291 --> 00:45:30,329
The man with gadgets on his head,

689
00:45:30,494 --> 00:45:32,405
the wires and everything.

690
00:45:52,049 --> 00:45:54,893
19 May, Palais de la Découverte

691
00:45:55,086 --> 00:45:59,865
The space capsule in which John Glenn
circled the Earth

692
00:46:01,158 --> 00:46:03,968
- Please, gentlemen.
- I've been on line for 3 hours.

693
00:46:04,128 --> 00:46:07,507
Yes, but look at all the people
behind you.

694
00:46:08,766 --> 00:46:10,336
Excuse me, but...

695
00:46:29,520 --> 00:46:31,522
Do you read about all this?

696
00:46:31,922 --> 00:46:34,903
Yes. The planets and stars.

697
00:46:35,993 --> 00:46:39,236
And about rockets too.

698
00:46:39,397 --> 00:46:42,241
You're interested in rockets'?

699
00:46:43,401 --> 00:46:45,472
What do you think of John Glenn?

700
00:46:45,836 --> 00:46:49,249
I like what he did.

701
00:46:49,407 --> 00:46:54,550
It's difficult to do what he did.

702
00:46:56,814 --> 00:47:01,456
To go up in a rocket
without being scared or...

703
00:47:02,953 --> 00:47:04,955
Don't you think he was scared?

704
00:47:05,122 --> 00:47:08,433
Maybe he was,
but not too scared.

705
00:47:11,829 --> 00:47:15,800
It's terrible for a genuine inventor
who has an idea.

706
00:47:15,966 --> 00:47:19,243
I don't mean a hunch.

707
00:47:19,437 --> 00:47:22,441
- His brain works nonstop, even asleep.
- Asleep?

708
00:47:30,915 --> 00:47:32,326
22 May, Paris Fair

709
00:47:32,483 --> 00:47:36,829
- Why the name "Destiny"?
- Because I've been through a lot.

710
00:47:36,987 --> 00:47:41,595
The first time I had a serious accident,

711
00:47:41,926 --> 00:47:45,271
I realized that I only survived

712
00:47:45,429 --> 00:47:47,409
because I was lucky.

713
00:47:47,565 --> 00:47:50,910
She was called "Malakoff"
because that was where I lived.

714
00:47:51,068 --> 00:47:56,313
I renamed her "Destiny"
as I was fated to surface.

715
00:47:56,474 --> 00:47:59,250
It's the story of my life.
My destiny.

716
00:47:59,410 --> 00:48:01,481
- You had a rough ride'?
- What?

717
00:48:01,645 --> 00:48:04,125
Lots of ups and downs'?

718
00:48:04,281 --> 00:48:06,022
My life's always been hard.

719
00:48:06,183 --> 00:48:09,995
I make it by the skin of my teeth,
every time.

720
00:48:10,154 --> 00:48:11,997
So luck is on my side.

721
00:48:12,156 --> 00:48:14,363
I always say: "It's destiny."

722
00:48:14,525 --> 00:48:17,904
What other accidents have you had?

723
00:48:18,062 --> 00:48:22,568
A breakdown once,
but I managed to scrape by.

724
00:48:22,933 --> 00:48:26,244
A spark plug burned out
in the middle of the Seine.

725
00:48:26,404 --> 00:48:28,543
The pier wasn't far off.

726
00:48:28,906 --> 00:48:31,352
I said:
"If I can't start, I crash."

727
00:48:31,509 --> 00:48:34,888
I try 4 or <i>5</i> times,
the pier gets closer.

728
00:48:35,045 --> 00:48:36,149
I'm heading for it.

729
00:48:36,313 --> 00:48:38,350
I have one more try...

730
00:48:38,516 --> 00:48:41,463
Like saying:
"In the name of the Father."

731
00:48:41,619 --> 00:48:45,294
The engine starts up.
That's destiny.

732
00:48:45,956 --> 00:48:48,197
Luck plays a big part in life.

733
00:48:48,359 --> 00:48:50,430
But the best luck is hands.

734
00:48:50,594 --> 00:48:53,268
They're the best capital you can have.

735
00:48:53,397 --> 00:48:56,241
These hands are my capital.

736
00:48:56,400 --> 00:49:01,543
A woman I know, a fine person,

737
00:49:01,705 --> 00:49:05,312
told me: "Son, your best capital
is your two hands.

738
00:49:05,476 --> 00:49:07,615
"You may have money in the bank,

739
00:49:07,978 --> 00:49:11,357
"but if you don't work
to keep up your account,

740
00:49:11,515 --> 00:49:12,357
"it falls apart."

741
00:49:12,516 --> 00:49:15,963
So in the end,
it all comes down to luck.

742
00:49:16,120 --> 00:49:18,293
And determination.

743
00:49:18,456 --> 00:49:22,632
If a man really wants to succeed
he can, he gets lucky.

744
00:49:23,461 --> 00:49:25,532
Of course, some people are unlucky.

745
00:49:25,696 --> 00:49:27,607
Do we make our own luck?

746
00:49:27,965 --> 00:49:30,104
We help it along?

747
00:49:30,267 --> 00:49:34,010
We do our bit
and luck does the rest.

748
00:49:34,171 --> 00:49:38,017
But luck is two hands
and the will to succeed.

749
00:49:38,175 --> 00:49:39,483
Like winning a war.

750
00:49:39,643 --> 00:49:43,386
- You have the will to succeed?
- I think so.

751
00:49:43,547 --> 00:49:45,026
Succeed in what?

752
00:49:45,182 --> 00:49:47,253
I want to make it.

753
00:49:47,418 --> 00:49:51,594
First, to prove to myself
that I'm capable of it.

754
00:49:51,755 --> 00:49:56,568
And I want to be well-known.

755
00:49:56,727 --> 00:49:59,230
That still bugs me.

756
00:49:59,396 --> 00:50:00,238
Why?

757
00:50:00,397 --> 00:50:04,140
Well, it's to do with my family.

758
00:50:04,301 --> 00:50:08,147
I said: "Right, I'm going to prove

759
00:50:08,305 --> 00:50:11,252
"that my name can be world famous."

760
00:50:11,408 --> 00:50:15,550
They've always seen me as...
Inventors are wacky.

761
00:50:15,713 --> 00:50:18,387
- Weaving spiders' webs?
- Exactly.

762
00:50:18,549 --> 00:50:21,359
But no matter,
we don't give a damn.

763
00:50:21,519 --> 00:50:24,261
What counts is the result.

764
00:50:24,421 --> 00:50:29,234
We say: "You guys
with your fancy equipment and stuff...

765
00:50:29,393 --> 00:50:31,737
"We work on a shoe string.

766
00:50:32,096 --> 00:50:34,542
"But we still get great results.

767
00:50:34,698 --> 00:50:37,406
"Here's the proof of it."

768
00:50:51,348 --> 00:50:53,726
- Are we doing 100'?
- Yes, 100.

769
00:50:54,084 --> 00:50:56,655
I can let go of the steering wheel.

770
00:50:56,820 --> 00:51:01,667
You'll see,
the car keeps on straight ahead.

771
00:51:01,825 --> 00:51:04,101
No danger whatsoever.

772
00:51:04,662 --> 00:51:07,404
We're on a track though.

773
00:51:07,765 --> 00:51:08,709
With the stabilizer.

774
00:51:09,066 --> 00:51:10,807
You say "we",
meaning all inventors?

775
00:51:11,168 --> 00:51:13,546
- Of course.
- Or you mean yourself?

776
00:51:13,704 --> 00:51:17,516
No, I'm thinking about the others,
we mustn't forget...

777
00:51:17,675 --> 00:51:20,588
I know a lot of private inventors.

778
00:51:20,744 --> 00:51:25,284
Some are helped by their wives
who encourage them.

779
00:51:25,449 --> 00:51:28,191
They're more resilient that others

780
00:51:28,352 --> 00:51:30,389
who are alone with no help.

781
00:51:30,554 --> 00:51:32,295
Inventors are men too.

782
00:51:32,489 --> 00:51:36,403
I think that's what is needed.

783
00:51:36,560 --> 00:51:40,702
Look at all the great statesmen,
without exception.

784
00:51:40,864 --> 00:51:43,811
There's always a woman behind them.

785
00:51:44,168 --> 00:51:47,149
It's beyond dispute.
It's been proved.

786
00:51:48,372 --> 00:51:51,080
Nowadays... take Churchill.

787
00:51:51,241 --> 00:51:55,621
When he made a speech
his wife was always at his side.

788
00:51:55,779 --> 00:51:59,556
All great men
have someone to help them.

789
00:51:59,717 --> 00:52:01,560
We need that spare wheel.

790
00:52:01,719 --> 00:52:03,756
You think Stalin had someone?

791
00:52:04,121 --> 00:52:08,228
Stalin is something else.
We don't know much about that aspect.

792
00:52:08,392 --> 00:52:09,427
We can't know.

793
00:52:09,593 --> 00:52:11,664
You think he had a muse?

794
00:52:11,829 --> 00:52:12,739
A what?

795
00:52:13,130 --> 00:52:13,630
Yes, the joy of making a home.

796
00:52:13,631 --> 00:52:15,838
Yes, the joy of making a home.

797
00:52:16,200 --> 00:52:20,342
Lots of young people like us
think about a home.

798
00:52:20,504 --> 00:52:23,644
Making it nice.

799
00:52:23,807 --> 00:52:25,753
A car. Going out.

800
00:52:25,909 --> 00:52:31,382
Going for drives...

801
00:52:32,683 --> 00:52:35,892
Going on holiday,
even going camping.

802
00:52:36,253 --> 00:52:38,494
- You like camping?
- I love it.

803
00:52:38,656 --> 00:52:40,397
- Do you, Mademoiselle?
- Yes.

804
00:52:40,557 --> 00:52:43,731
She hasn't done much
but she'll love it.

805
00:52:43,927 --> 00:52:45,372
And the others?

806
00:52:45,529 --> 00:52:47,668
- What others?
- All the others.

807
00:52:47,831 --> 00:52:49,902
I think they're like us.

808
00:52:52,369 --> 00:52:53,245
Why not'?

809
00:52:54,505 --> 00:52:56,917
Why can't you compare them to us?

810
00:52:57,274 --> 00:53:01,620
There aren't many of them, like us.

811
00:53:01,779 --> 00:53:04,919
What's the difference?
They love each other less?

812
00:53:05,282 --> 00:53:06,784
No, but it's not the same.

813
00:53:06,950 --> 00:53:08,395
Meaning?

814
00:53:11,655 --> 00:53:16,331
You mean it's always been
very serious between us.

815
00:53:17,394 --> 00:53:18,566
It's been six years?

816
00:53:19,697 --> 00:53:22,337
- How old are you'?
- We're both 21.

817
00:53:22,499 --> 00:53:25,173
- I'm 21 tomorrow.
- 21 tomorrow.

818
00:53:26,303 --> 00:53:29,546
We were 15 when we met.

819
00:53:29,707 --> 00:53:31,584
We've always been faithful.

820
00:53:31,742 --> 00:53:34,416
- At first, just friends.
- We were only 15.

821
00:53:34,578 --> 00:53:37,218
We didn't see each other often...

822
00:53:38,348 --> 00:53:40,851
But we always hoped we would.

823
00:53:41,218 --> 00:53:41,958
Were you neighbors?

824
00:53:42,486 --> 00:53:45,729
Not at all.
We weren't so lucky.

825
00:53:45,889 --> 00:53:47,869
We met at a wedding.

826
00:54:00,904 --> 00:54:02,212
Smile.

827
00:56:13,737 --> 00:56:15,876
Once you're married with kids,

828
00:56:16,039 --> 00:56:18,383
what will you want for them?

829
00:56:18,542 --> 00:56:19,680
For them?

830
00:56:19,843 --> 00:56:23,985
We'll try to give them
the best life we can.

831
00:56:24,147 --> 00:56:28,823
Sure. We don't know what sort,
it depends on them.

832
00:56:28,986 --> 00:56:31,125
On what they want and...

833
00:56:31,488 --> 00:56:33,934
But they probably won't be like us.

834
00:56:34,091 --> 00:56:38,801
Does it depend on the world?
Do you see clouds ahead?

835
00:56:42,599 --> 00:56:44,442
Apart from illness.

836
00:56:44,601 --> 00:56:47,741
Yes, of course.
Otherwise I don't see...

837
00:56:47,905 --> 00:56:50,408
Ever think about major events?

838
00:56:50,574 --> 00:56:56,081
I don't want to think about all that.
Once you start...

839
00:56:56,446 --> 00:56:59,017
Anyway, it's out of our hands.

840
00:56:59,182 --> 00:57:02,129
No, I don't want to think about that.

841
00:57:02,486 --> 00:57:05,092
- There's nothing we can do.
- Nothing?

842
00:57:05,455 --> 00:57:08,026
No. We can't take it into account.

843
00:57:08,191 --> 00:57:11,434
There's no point worrying about it.

844
00:57:11,595 --> 00:57:14,474
I'm off to Algeria soon.

845
00:57:14,631 --> 00:57:18,545
I'm leaving in about ten days.

846
00:57:18,702 --> 00:57:21,842
I know it all happens that way.

847
00:57:22,005 --> 00:57:25,179
I'm not making a thing of it.
I'm going there...

848
00:57:25,542 --> 00:57:30,514
I don't dare think about it.
I don't want to.

849
00:57:30,681 --> 00:57:34,629
So there are no problems
outside your own happiness?

850
00:57:39,089 --> 00:57:42,866
I don't want to think
about historical events...

851
00:57:43,026 --> 00:57:47,441
Do you feel solidarity toward people
less happy than you'?

852
00:57:53,904 --> 00:57:56,111
There aren't many of them?

853
00:57:56,940 --> 00:58:00,717
Yes, there are.
But anyway...

854
00:58:01,645 --> 00:58:04,148
I don't know.
If everyone was like us...

855
00:58:04,514 --> 00:58:05,515
It would be...

856
00:58:05,682 --> 00:58:08,891
It would be nice.
We get on with everyone.

857
00:58:09,052 --> 00:58:11,464
Yes, but...

858
00:58:11,621 --> 00:58:16,229
I say people can do what they like.

859
00:58:16,593 --> 00:58:18,539
But you have your own opinion?

860
00:58:22,666 --> 00:58:25,237
When you have children,
will it change a bit?

861
00:58:25,602 --> 00:58:28,139
Maybe as we get older...

862
00:58:29,139 --> 00:58:30,243
Yes, possibly.

863
00:58:30,607 --> 00:58:33,087
How do you feel about growing old?

864
00:58:33,243 --> 00:58:37,919
Do you think your happiness
will last, will it change?

865
00:58:38,749 --> 00:58:40,057
I hope so.

866
00:58:41,184 --> 00:58:43,255
Do you ever think about it'?

867
00:58:44,588 --> 00:58:48,798
I don't know,
but I believe we're happy.

868
00:58:48,959 --> 00:58:53,669
Some people say
after years of marriage you get a bit...

869
00:58:53,830 --> 00:58:57,573
I believe in eternal happiness.

870
00:58:58,168 --> 00:59:02,583
<i>End of Part One</i>

871
